#Text=Tacuarembó
#Text=Tacuarembó is a town in the Northern Interior region of Uruguay with approximately 50,000 inhabitants .
#Text=It is popular for both being an important center for gaucho culture and for being one of the presumed birthplaces of Carlos Gardel , perhaps the most prominent figure in the history of tango .
#Text=By bus
#Text=From Montevideo , buses leave from Terminal Tres Cruces , and the 5h ride costs around 800 UYU ( 28 USD , Mar 2018 ) .
#Text=Timetable , companies and prices can be checked at its website .

#Text=From Porto Alegre in Brazil , companies Turil go all the way to Tacuarembó two times a week ( leaves Porto Alegre Mondays and Fridays 23h15 , 170 BRL or 50 USD , and goes back to Porto Alegre Sundays and Thursdays 21h30 , 2.938 UYU or 103 USD , tip : buy all your tickets from the Brazilian version of their website ) .

#Text=But it is cheaper to take a bus from Porto Alegre to Santana do Livramento ( 7h , 100 BRL or 30 USD ) , walk across the border to Rivera ( do n't forget to pass on the immigration post ) , and take a onward bus to Tacuarembó ( 2h , 240 UYU or 8 USD ) .
#Text=From Rivera to Tacuarembó , the Mon - Sat timetable is : 4h30* , 6h , 7h , 10h , 15h* , 15h30* , 19h ( * Sunday service ) .
#Text=Get around
#Text=Tacuarembó
#Text=town is fairly small and easily walkable .
#Text=However , a good number of attractions lie out of town and you 'll need your own transport to reach them .
#Text=See
#Text=Carlos Gardel Museum , kilometer # 208 on route 26 ( Go 23km south from the city of Tacuarembó via 26 route heading Paysandú . ) .
#Text=Thursday to Sunday 8am to 5pm .

#Text=Largely dedicated to present evidence that the tango legend was actually born in Uruguay ( and not in Argentina or France , as usually believed ) , the museum counts with a nice selection of newspaper articles and other documents .
#Text=It 's a nice insight into a less formal era , when name , age , parents or nationality could easily be concealed .
#Text=The museum buildings are a reproduction of the nearby estancia in which Gardel would have been born .
#Text=25 UYU .
#Text=Gaucho and Indian Museum ( Museo del Indio y del Gaucho ) , corner of av . General Artigas and Av. General Flores .
#Text=El Hongo , corner of av . República Argentina and calle Manuel Rodríguez Correa .
#Text=A giant work of public art that supposedly resembles a mushroom , created by Walter Domingo , an architect who created several other important works in Tacuarembó Department .
#Text=With the work , Domingo wanted to represent the atomic bombs dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki .
#Text=Do
#Text=Laguna de las Lavanderas ( Washerwomen Lagoon ) ( head North until you cross the bridge ) .
#Text=Besides being the heart of Gaucho culture during the Fiesta de la Patria Gaucha , the lagoon is also a favorite place for locals to go drink mate in late afternoon
#Text=Valle Edén , kilometer # 208 on route 26 ( Go 23km south from the city of Tacuarembó via 26 route heading Paysandú . ) .
#Text=Valle Edén is a mountain range zone with a subtropical vegetation .
#Text=The " arroyo jabonería " , " la gruta de los galpones " and the " Carlos Gardel " museum are must see places for tourists .
#Text=There is wooden suspension bridge , an old train station and some railroad tracks too .
#Text=Balneario Ypora ( 7km away from Tacuarembó roundabout near the northern bridge ) .
#Text=A lagoon surrounded by grass and some pine trees , popular on sunny days for some water fun , sun-bathing and drinking mate .
#Text=Nearby is the Indian Cemetery which has been in continuous use since precolumbian times .
#Text=Cerro Batoví ( 25 km from the city of Tacuarembó
#Text=take route 5 heading south to Paso de los Toros ) .
#Text=The 224 meters mountain is a symbol included in the " Escudo del Departamento " ( departamental shield ) .

column1: #Text=Its name Batoví means " virgin 's breast " in the Guarani language .
#Text=Fiesta de la Patria Gaucha
#Text=This big event celebrating regional countryside life and customs takes place annually on the second weekend of March , on Lavanderas Lake .
#Text=It remains a very traditional event , with most attendees being somehow connected to gaucho culture of Northern Uruguay .
#Text=Official website : https://www.patriagaucha.com.uy/
#Text=It is structured as a competition between gaucho culture groups , the sociedades criollas , most located in nearby villages .

#Text=A group of them , Sociedades Participantes , competes for the fair big prize , while another group , Sociedades Invitadas , competes for the right to join the Sociedades Participantes on the year to come .
#Text=Tournaments counting points for the sociedades include :
#Text=many types of horse and bull riding ( rodeo )
#Text=best rancho - which is a historically accurate reconstruction of some remarkable area relevant to the gaucho history , complete with buildings , furniture , artifacts and usually cuisine .
#Text=Themes of choice are usually estancias of respected people , rural schools , rural train stations or even a cheese factories of 1800s or early 1900s .
#Text=best dish - and you can buy vouchers at the fair central office ( administración ) to taste it as well !
#Text=flor del pago ( village flower ) - the lady who 'll represent the gaucho nation in other events .
#Text=It 's not a beauty pageant , she is instead selected for her horse-riding ability and eloquence
#Text=little peasant ( girl and boy ) - best old times children
#Text=presentation ( they usually come riding their own horses even at tender ages ! )
#Text=On the festival Saturday , all the sociedades ( including those not competing ) leave in a horse parade that crosses Tacuarembó town , from 9h to midday .
#Text=Locals estimate between 3 to 5 thousand horses .
#Text=Once finished , there 's an act in front of General Artigas statue on the main square , after which is a great opportunity for pictures with gauchos and their horses .
#Text=On the festival Sunday , a gaucho mass is celebrated just outside the festival venue .
#Text=Tickets

#Text=Entrance to the general area costs 300 UYU or less ( inquire about discounts at the ticket office , since in 2018 tickets bought with BROU cards received a 2nd free ticket - up to 5 combos / 10 tickets per card ) .
#Text=The ticket is valid for the whole day .
#Text=It 's possible to leave the area and go back with the same ticket , just ask for the return voucher on your way out ( but bear in mind these vouchers are only handed till 22h ) .
#Text=Most people spend the day at the fair , leave in the evening ( rest and take shower ) , and come back at night for the concerts .
#Text=Entrance to the rodeos vary with day/seat area , but could be as cheap as 100 UYU .
#Text=There 's an independent ticket booth for each tribune , so inquire prices and shade situation first .
